message.content:
To be generated, the string must come from one of the two start-rules

1. S → NT23 NT21  
2. S → NT120 NT47

Rule 1 places the very first terminal produced by the grammar inside NT23.  
NT23 has only one lexical production: NT23 → ‘t120’.  
So any sentence derived via rule 1 must begin with t120.  
Our sentence begins with t156, therefore rule 1 is impossible.

Hence S must use rule 2 and end with whatever NT47 produces.

NT47 has exactly two productions:

NT47 → NT68 NT84          (rightmost terminal is whatever NT84 gives)  
NT47 → NT88 NT88          (rightmost terminal is whatever the second NT88 gives)

NT84 is lexical, producing only  t206, t156 or t45.  
NT88 is lexical, producing only  t127 or t136.  

Consequently, every string generated via rule 2 must end with  
t206, t156, t45, t127 or t136.

The given string ends with t38, which is none of these.  
Therefore rule 2 is also impossible, and the grammar cannot generate the string.

No

The start symbol S has only two productions:

1. S → NT23 NT21  
   NT23 is a lexical non-terminal with the single rule NT23 → 't120'.  
   Therefore any string generated via this production must begin with the
   terminal t120.  
   The given string begins with t127, so this production cannot derive the
   string.

2. S → NT120 NT47  
   NT47 can be expanded only as  
      NT47 → NT68 NT84 or NT47 → NT88 NT88.  
   In both cases the rightmost terminal produced by NT47 is determined by the
   lexical non-terminals NT84 or NT88:  
      • NT84 can generate only t206, t45, or t156.  
      • NT88 can generate only t127 or t136 (and if NT47 → NT88 NT88, the last
        two terminals of the whole string must therefore both be t127 or t136).

   The last terminal of the given string is t127, but the one before it is
   t23.  Hence the suffix of the string cannot be produced by either NT68 NT84
   (because the final token would have to be t206/t45/t156) or by NT88 NT88
   (because the last two tokens would both have to be t127/t136).  Therefore
   NT47 cannot derive the tail of the string, so the production S → NT120 NT47
   cannot derive the whole string either.

Since neither of the only two possible derivations from S can produce the
given 31-token string, the string is not in the language of the grammar.

No
